    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-06-19T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-06-19T19:00:00-05:00" n="155"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d155">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">891.24/203: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Iran</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dreyfus</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-06-19T20:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 19, 1942—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>162. Your 192, June 9, last three paragraphs.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Formal Lend-Lease agreement with Iran is contemplated and will be drawn up
                        in due course. It is proposed to conclude agreements with United Nations
                        before beginning negotiations with other countries.</item>
                    <pb facs="0150" n="138" xml:id="pg_138"/>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Lend-Lease will probably be handled on same general basis as other
                        Government orders. Requests would be channeled through Central Supplies
                        Committee and MESC before presentation to Lend-Lease Administration here.
                        Exact manner of delivery in Iran has not yet been decided. Question of
                        Lend-Lease delivery and distribution in Iran is under consideration here and
                        decision will probably depend largely upon ultimate composition of Tehran
                        Central Supplies Committee and the attitude adopted by the British regarding
                        use of that committee to supervise supply distribution. Question may also be
                        affected by appointment of American supply adviser, if satisfactory man is
                        obtained.</item>
                </list>
                <p>In talking with Prime Minister, you should emphasize American participation in
                    MESC. An officer of the Department<note n="29" xml:id="d155fn29">Frederick
                        Winant of the Division of Exports and Defense Aid.</note> will shortly
                    proceed to Cairo to head our representation on that body.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
